The Z' factor is calculated as follows:

Z' = 1 - \frac{3(\sigma_p + \sigma_n)}{|\mu_n - \mu_p|}  
= 1 - \frac{3(2 + 5)}{|100 - 10|}  
= 1 - \frac{21}{90}  
= 1 - 0.2333  
= 0.7667 (approximately 0.77)

Interpretation: A Z' factor > 0.5 indicates an excellent assay suitable for high-throughput screening. With a value of 0.77, this assay is considered to have excellent quality.
